.TH CPCLIP 1 "2026" "cpclip" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
cpclip, cpadd, cppaste, cpclear \- command-line clipboard for X11 and Wayland
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B cpclip
.RI [ TEXT ]
.RB [ \-t
.IR MIME ]
.RB [ \-f ]
.RB [ \-\-backend
.IR NAME ]
.br
.B cpadd
.RI [ TEXT ]
.RB [ \-t
.IR MIME ]
.RB [ \-\-separator
.IR STR ]
.RB [ \-f ]
.RB [ \-\-backend
.IR NAME ]
.br
.B cppaste
.RB [ \-t
.IR MIME ]
.RB [ \-n ]
.RB [ \-\-backend
.IR NAME ]
.br
.B cpclear
.RB [ \-\-backend
.IR NAME ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
One binary with four faces, selected by the name it is invoked as. It captures
process output to the system clipboard and serves the clipboard back to process
input, on both X11 and Wayland, behind one identical command interface.
.TP
.B cpclip
Read standard input (or the
.I TEXT
argument) and replace the clipboard with it.
.TP
.B cpadd
Append standard input (or
.IR TEXT )
to the clipboard, joined by a separator (default newline). On an empty
clipboard this is identical to
.BR cpclip .
It refuses to overwrite a non-text selection.
.TP
.B cppaste
Write the clipboard to standard output.
.TP
.B cpclear
Relinquish ownership so the clipboard becomes empty.
.PP
Because X11 and Wayland have no system-owned clipboard buffer, the copying
process itself is the storage:
.B cpclip
and
.B cpadd
fork a background process that owns the selection and serves it on demand. The
parent does not exit until that child confirms ownership. A running clipboard
manager (e.g. KDE's) typically takes over and provides persistence after the
owner exits.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-t " MIME" "\fR, \fP" \-\-type " MIME"
Content type. On copy it is advertised (and served) alongside the default text
set; on paste it is the preferred type to request.
.TP
.BR \-\-separator " " \fISTR\fP
.RB ( cpadd
only) String placed between the existing content and the appended content.
Defaults to a newline.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-no\-newline
.RB ( cppaste
only) Do not append a trailing newline. By default a single newline is appended
only when the data does not already end with one. Use
.B \-n
for byte-exact binary output.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-foreground
.RB ( cpclip ", " cpadd
only) Stay in the foreground and serve the selection until another client takes
it, instead of forking into the background.
.TP
.BR \-m ", " \-\-maxmem " " \fISIZE\fP
.RB ( cpclip ", " cpadd
only) Cap the input size.
.I SIZE
accepts a binary K/M/G suffix (e.g.\&
.IR 200M ).
The default is 10 MiB and 0 disables the cap. Because the owner holds the whole
payload in memory, this guards against an accidental huge input pinning RAM.
.TP
.BR \-\-backend " " \fINAME\fP
Force a backend:
.BR x11 ", " wayland ", " null ", or " auto
(the default). Auto selects Wayland when
.B $WAYLAND_DISPLAY
is set, else X11 when
.B $DISPLAY
is set.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print usage and exit.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print the version and exit.
.SH "TERMINAL PASS-THROUGH"
.B cpclip
and
.B cpadd
mirror standard input to standard output only when standard output is a
terminal, so
.RB ` "cmd | cpclip" `
shows the output and copies it, while
.RB ` "cmd | cpclip | other" `
copies silently without disturbing the pipeline.
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Runtime error (no display server, unreadable selection, etc.).
.TP
.B 2
Usage error (unknown invocation name or inapplicable flag).
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B WAYLAND_DISPLAY
If set, the
.B auto
backend uses Wayland.
.TP
.B DISPLAY
If set (and Wayland is not), the
.B auto
backend uses X11.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Copy a command's output and also see it:
.PP
.RS
.nf
make 2>&1 | cpclip
.fi
.RE
.PP
Accumulate several outputs into one clipboard entry:
.PP
.RS
.nf
git rev-parse HEAD | cpclip
date              | cpadd
uname -a          | cpadd
cppaste
.fi
.RE
.PP
Paste byte-exact binary data:
.PP
.RS
.nf
cppaste -n > image.png
.fi
.RE
.SH NOTES
All clipboard payloads are handled as raw bytes, so NUL bytes and arbitrary
binary survive a round trip. Primary and secondary selections are not supported.
With a running clipboard manager,
.B cpclear
may be immediately undone by the manager restoring its history.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR wl\-clipboard (1),
.BR xclip (1),
.BR xsel (1)
